messages.content: You are tasked with creating a structured output from the provided user message.

- Full HTTP request path: /consumer/subscribe

- All HTTP methods acceptable (overrides per-request results): true

- HEAD: true
- POST: true
- OPTIONS: true
- TRACE: true
- GET: true
- PUT: true
- DELETE: true
- PATCH: true

Explanation:
- The subscribe handler is declared as:
  @RequestMapping(value = "/consumer/subscribe", produces = "text/event-stream")
  with no method attribute. In Spring MVC, an @RequestMapping that does not specify a RequestMethod maps to all HTTP methods. Therefore the endpoint accepts all methods (HEAD, GET, POST, PUT, DELETE, PATCH, OPTIONS, TRACE) according to the controller code.
- There is no class-level @RequestMapping on NotificationsController to add a prefix, so the full path is exactly "/consumer/subscribe".
- The determination is made purely from the source code shown (absence of method restriction on @RequestMapping) and does not rely on runtime or server behavior assumptions.
